      "cell_type": "markdown",

        "id": "nr3vZbSfe0Aq"
      },
      "source": [
        "# Exploring PyDMD\n",
        "\n",
        "The DMD method originated from the fluid dynamics community as a method to decompose transient complex flows into \"modes\" based on spatiotemporal coherent structures. The method can be interpreted as a combination of (i) PCA in the sense of spatial dimensionality reduction and (ii) frequecy-based temporal analysis such as Fourier transformations. Similar to PCA, we will get components -- now called modes -- and we will look how these modes evolve in time. The objective is to ease the analysis of coherent structures observed in high dimensional systems in a different coordinate system. This temporal behaviour is typically analyzed as temporal frequency, possibly with a growth or decay rate. \n",
        "\n",
        "DMD is algorithmically a regression of data onto locally linear dynamics. it is very simple to perform and it makes almost no assumptions about the underlying system. Potential applications are:\n",
        "\n",
        "+ diagnostic tool to characterize complex fluid flows,\n",
        "+ state estimation and future-state prediction,\n",
        "+ ultimately, data-driven approach to control."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "H8ytu5oW3HiR"
      },
      "source": [
        "## Lets start with the base model\n",
        "\n",
        "Lets see the implementation of a very basic, text book example. We will have 2 signals, which will have different frequencies in time, merging into a more complex output:\n",
        "\n",
        "$\\\n",
        "f_1(x,t) = \\text{sech}(x)\\exp(i1.618t)\n",
        "$\n",
        "\n",
        "$\\\n",
        "f_2(x,t) = \\tanh(x)\\exp(i0.618t)\n",
        "$\n",
        "\n",
        "Above you can follow the spatial and temporal dependencies explicitly, which we would not know in a real, data driven case. Lets generate our data from these functions:\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "AJiTv8qj4iGI"
      },
      "source": [
        "# Function definitions:\n",
        "def f1(t,x): \n",
        "    return 1./np.cosh(x)*np.exp(1.618j*t)\n",
        "def f2(t,x):\n",
        "    return 1*np.tanh(x)*np.exp(0.618j*t)\n",
        "#----------------------------------\n",
        "#Creating the independent variables:\n",
        "x = np.linspace(-6, 6, 400)\n",
        "t = np.linspace(0, 4*np.pi, 200)\n",
        "# creating coordinate matrices from coordinate vectors:\n",
        "tgrid, xgrid = np.meshgrid(t,x)\n",
        "# calling the functions:\n",
        "X1 = f1(tgrid, xgrid)\n",
        "X2 = f2(tgrid, xgrid)\n",
        "X = X1 + X2"
      ],
      "execution_count": 39,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {

      },

        "print(X.shape)"

      ]

      "cell_type": "code",

          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"

        "id": "n2Xt4fUK7pCM",

      },
      "source": [
        "#https://mathlab.github.io/PyDMD/dmdbase.html\n",
        "#\n",
        "#Hyperparameters:\n",
        "#----------------\n",
        "#the rank for the truncation; If 0, the method computes the optimal rank and uses it for truncation; \n",
        "#if positive interger, the method uses the argument for the truncation; \n",
        "#if float between 0 and 1, the rank is the number of the biggest singular values that are needed \n",
        "#to reach the ‘energy’ specified by svd_rank.\n",
        "#----------------\n",
        "svd_rank=2\n",
        "#Calling the model:\n",
        "dmd = DMD(svd_rank=svd_rank)\n",
        "# 'Training' the model:Compute the Dynamic Modes Decomposition to the input data.\n",
        "dmd.fit(X)"
      ],

      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "uXMqIqp1EPY0"
      },
      "source": [
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "The dmd object contains the information about the decomposition:\n",
        "\n",
        "https://mathlab.github.io/PyDMD/dmdbase.html\n",
        "\n",
        "`modes`: Get the matrix containing the DMD modes, stored by column\n",
        "\n",
        "`dynamics`: Get the time evolution of each mode.\n",
        "\n",
        "`eigs`: Plot the eigenvalues. :param bool show_axes: if True, the axes will be showed in the plot.\n",
        "\n",
        "`reconstructed_data`: Get the reconstructed data.\n",
        "\n",
        "`plot_modes_2D`: Plot the DMD Modes.\n",
        "\n",
        "`plot_eigs`: Plot the eigenvalues. :param bool show_axes: if True, the axes will be showed in the plot.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Note:**\n",
        "\n",
        "The eigen values helps us to determine whether the modes are stable or not: \n",
        "\n",
        "+ if an eigenvalue is on the unit circle, the corresponding mode will be stable; \n",
        "\n",
        "+ if an eigenvalue is inside or outside the unit circle, the mode will converge or diverge, respectively. Let see our case:"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",

        "for eig in dmd.eigs:\n",
        "    print('Eigenvalue {}: distance from unit circle {}'.format(eig, np.abs(eig.imag**2+eig.real**2 - 1)))"

        "As the next step, we can reconstruct dynamics of the system as the product of modes and dynamics."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "CavhhWbl5Fyc"
      },
      "source": [
        "dy =dmd.dynamics[0].reshape(1,-1)"
      ],
      "execution_count": 66,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "8D7_QcTO4Sww"
      },
      "source": [
        "#Getting the modes\n",
        "DM1 = dmd.modes.T[0].reshape(-1,1).dot(dmd.dynamics[0].reshape(1,-1))\n",
        "DM2 = dmd.modes.T[1].reshape(-1,1).dot(dmd.dynamics[1].reshape(1,-1))"
      ],

            ]
          },
          "metadata": {
            "tags": [],
            "needs_background": "light"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "6ZMXbApzNDhG"
      },
      "source": [
        "We see that there are some minor errors but the reconstruction is very well. \n",
        "\n",
        "The next question is; can we do better? Can we forecast into the future with the learnt dynamics? For that,lets look at a more complex problem."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "TpgZGqP8PIy4"
      },
      "source": [
        "# Advanced tuning and forecasting with DMD\n",
        "\n",
        "Here we will crate a temporal, 2D oscillation with noise, to make things more difficult for DMD:\n",
        "\n",
        "Here is the ground truth:\n",
        "\n",
        "$\\\n",
        "f(x,y,t) := \\text{senh}(x) * \\text{senh}(y)*1.2\\text{i}^{-t}\n",
        "$\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "De9bA25nP3RA"
      },
      "source": [
        "#Creating the grid:\n",
        "x1 = np.linspace(-5, 5, 100)\n",
        "x2 = np.linspace(-5, 5, 100)\n",
        "x1grid, x2grid = np.meshgrid(x1, x2)\n",
        "# temporal data\n",
        "time = np.linspace(0, 5, 20)\n",
        "# getting the f over the grid points:\n",
        "data = [2/np.cosh(x1grid)/np.cosh(x2grid)*(1.2j**-t) for t in time]\n",
        "# creating random noise:\n",
        "noise = [np.random.normal(0.0, 0.33, size=x1grid.shape) for t in time]\n",
        "# combining the true values and the noise:\n",
        "snapshots = [d+n for d,n in zip(data, noise)]\n"
      ],
      "execution_count": 14,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/",
          "height": 918
        },
        "id": "7cVLJB_wRco9",
        "outputId": "2951e46d-c595-4f4c-c131-b24d434aa191"
      },
      "source": [
        "# Lets see how it looks like:\n",
        "fig = plt.figure(figsize=(18,16))\n",
        "for id_subplot, snapshot in enumerate(snapshots, start=1):\n",
        "    plt.subplot(5, 4, id_subplot)\n",
        "    plt.pcolor(x1grid, x2grid, snapshot.real, vmin=-1, vmax=1)"
      ],
      "execution_count": 15,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "display_data",
          "data": {
            "image/png": "\n",
            "text/plain": [
              "<Figure size 1296x1152 with 20 Axes>"
            ]
          },
          "metadata": {
            "tags": [],
            "needs_background": "light"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "konmTT_1bVlq"
      },
      "source": [
        "## Applying DMD to the snapshots\n",
        "\n",
        "Okay, now the magic trick! We will apply again the DMD on the dataset. Now lets epand our control over hyperparameters!"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "yY0Hc8T7bkv0",
        "outputId": "b44a5c64-fcd8-49fc-a20b-cd31d766e501"
      },
      "source": [
        "#https://mathlab.github.io/PyDMD/dmdbase.html\n",
        "#\n",
        "#Hyperparameters:\n",
        "#class DMDBase(svd_rank=0, tlsq_rank=0, exact=False, opt=False, rescale_mode=None, forward_backward=False, sorted_eigs=False)\n",
        "#----------------\n",
        "#the rank for the truncation; If 0, the method computes the optimal rank and uses it for truncation; \n",
        "#if positive interger, the method uses the argument for the truncation; \n",
        "#if float between 0 and 1, the rank is the number of the biggest singular values that are needed \n",
        "#to reach the ‘energy’ specified by svd_rank.\n",
        "svd_rank=1\n",
        "#----------------\n",
        "#tlsq_rank (int) – rank truncation computing Total Least Square. Default is 0, that means no truncation.\n",
        "# we can use it to remove or reduce the noise in the data.\n",
        "tlsq_rank=2\n",
        "#----------------\n",
        "#exact (bool) – flag to compute either exact DMD or projected DMD. Default is False.\n",
        "exact = True\n",
        "#----------------\n",
        "#opt (bool or int) – If True, amplitudes are computed like in optimized DMD \n",
        "#(see https://mathlab.github.io/PyDMD/_summaries/pydmd.dmdbase.DMDBase._compute_amplitudes.html) \n",
        "#If False, amplitudes are computed following the standard algorithm\n",
        "opt = True\n",
        "#----------------\n",
        "#Calling the model:\n",
        "dmd = DMD(svd_rank=svd_rank, tlsq_rank=tlsq_rank, exact=exact, opt=opt)\n",
        "# 'Training' the model:Compute the Dynamic Modes Decomposition to the input data.\n",
        "dmd.fit(snapshots)"
      ],
      "execution_count": 16,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "execute_result",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": [
              "<pydmd.dmd.DMD at 0x7f738c45b3d0>"
            ]
          },
          "metadata": {
            "tags": []
          },
          "execution_count": 16
        }

        "### How to define the rank?\n",
        "\n",
        "We have to options to select the rank: we can either set it to be decided automatically by setting `svd_rank` to zero. Alternatively, we can check the relative importance of SVDs and set it by ourselves, like we did in 'Clustering' algorithms in DDE-1.\n"
      ]

      "cell_type": "code",

          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"

      "source": [
        "#Original data set shape\n",
        "print(\"Original data set shape: {}\".format(dmd.reconstructed_data.shape))\n",
        "#-----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "# Generating data: see variables under:\n",
        "#https://mathlab.github.io/PyDMD/dmdbase.html\n",
        "#-----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "#dmd_time is a dictionary that contains information about the time window \n",
        "# where the system is reconstructed:\n",
        "#        t0 is the time of the first approximated solution;\n",
        "#        tend is the time of the last approximated solution;\n",
        "#        dt is the delta time between the approximated solutions.\n",
        "#-----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "dmd.dmd_time['dt'] *= 0.20\n",
        "dmd.dmd_time['tend'] *= 2\n",
        "print(\"Modified data shape: {}\".format(dmd.reconstructed_data.shape))"
      ],
      "execution_count": 23,

      "source": [
        "### Global evaluation of the forecasting\n",
        "\n",
        "Lets simplfy the data with integration over the surface and see the evalaution of the pulsations in time. It may give us an idea about the overall performance of the reconstruction."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/",
          "height": 334
        },
        "id": "bUYjBbr_yCca",
        "outputId": "d71e3282-efe9-4950-8aaa-fff710070581"
      },
      "source": [
        "#Picking an integration scheme; 2D => 1D plot\n",
        "compute_integral = scipy.integrate.simps\n",
        "\n",
        "true_data = [compute_integral(compute_integral(snapshot)).real for snapshot in snapshots]\n",
        "dmd_generated = [compute_integral(compute_integral(state)).real for state in dmd_states]\n",
        "\n",
        "figure = plt.figure(figsize=(18, 5))\n",
        "plt.plot(dmd.original_timesteps, true_data, 'ko', linewidth=3, label='true_data')\n",
        "plt.plot(dmd.dmd_timesteps, dmd_generated, 'b.', label='dmd_generated')\n",
        "plt.ylabel('Integrated data')\n",
        "plt.xlabel('time')\n",
        "plt.grid()\n",
        "leg = plt.legend()"
      ],
      "execution_count": 26,

        "# More fun example: flow around the buildings\n",

        "This time we will look at a single phase flow problem. The case is from the tutorial library of OpenFOAM:\n",

      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "_wCRPAUR_PRl"
      },
      "source": [
        "## Forward-Backward DMD\n",
        "\n",
        "Like any data processing technique, DMD's usefulness is limited by its ability to extract real and accurate dynamical features from noise-corrupted data. In order to remove numerical noise,  here we will apply a remedy called Forward-Backward DMD:\n",
        "\n",
        "https://arxiv.org/abs/1507.02264"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "o-bzZuuJ_WMQ",
        "outputId": "b81170a6-772f-4526-b4e8-4f4975e3158d"
      },
      "source": [
        "#FbDMD: It has the same attributes and methods of the DMD class. \n",
        "#------------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "#class FbDMD(svd_rank=0, tlsq_rank=0, exact=False, opt=False, rescale_mode=None, sorted_eigs=False)\n",
        "#https://mathlab.github.io/PyDMD/fbdmd.html\n",
        "# forward-backward version reduces the error by computing the low-rank linear operator\n",
        "# as the square root of the product between the operator for the forward evolution and \n",
        "# the operator for the backward evolution.\n",
        "##------------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "#Create object\n",
        "fbdmd = FbDMD(exact=True)\n",
        "#'Fitting':\n",
        "fbdmd.fit(snapshots)\n",
        "fbdmd.reconstructed_data.shape"
      ],
      "execution_count": 33,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "execute_result",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": [
              "(7219, 20)"
            ]
          },
          "metadata": {
            "tags": []
          },
          "execution_count": 33
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "NyGHWxAqA2Lr",
        "outputId": "6303e854-80b0-491d-acf6-d886bafab634"
      },
      "source": [
        "#Lets see how much it is better than good old DMD. We can check the eigen values of both method:\n",
        "\n",
        "# Good-old-DMD:\n",
        "dmd = DMD(exact=True)\n",
        "dmd.fit(snapshots)\n",
        "print('[ DMD ] Total distance between eigenvalues and unit circle: {}'.format(\n",
        "    np.sum(np.abs(dmd.eigs.real**2 + dmd.eigs.imag**2 - 1))\n",
        "))\n",
        "print('[FbDMD] Total distance between eigenvalues and unit circle: {}'.format(\n",
        "    np.sum(np.abs(fbdmd.eigs.real**2 + fbdmd.eigs.imag**2 - 1))\n",
        "))"
      ],
      "execution_count": 34,
      "outputs": [

        "Lets do the same trick for generating new data and creating a video out of it:"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "9gPc7XoADMEf",
        "outputId": "549ac03c-93fe-400c-a328-047076909cae"
      },
      "source": [
        "#Lets do the same trick:\n",
        "print(\"Original data set shape: {}\".format(fbdmd.reconstructed_data.shape))\n",
        "#-----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "# Generating data: see variables under:\n",
        "#https://mathlab.github.io/PyDMD/dmdbase.html\n",
        "#-----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "#dmd_time is a dictionary that contains information about the time window \n",
        "# where the system is reconstructed:\n",
        "#        t0 is the time of the first approximated solution;\n",
        "#        tend is the time of the last approximated solution;\n",
        "#        dt is the delta time between the approximated solutions.\n",
        "#-----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "fbdmd.dmd_time['dt'] *= 0.20\n",
        "fbdmd.dmd_time['tend'] *= 4\n",
        "print(\"Modified data shape: {}\".format(fbdmd.reconstructed_data.shape))"
      ],
      "execution_count": 36,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "text": [

            "Modified data shape: (7219, 381)\n"
          ],
          "name": "stdout"
        }

        "# Now lets take the advantage of using ipython and create an video from the images we generated:\n",
        "# base figure\n",
        "fig = plt.figure()\n",
        "# generating data\n",
        "dmd_states = [state.reshape(7219) for state in fbdmd.reconstructed_data.T]\n",
        "print(len(dmd_states))\n",
        "# Hidden nested loop: \n",
        "frames = [[plt.scatter(pts[:, 0], pts[:, 1], c=state, marker='.')] for state in dmd_states ]\n",
        "#Note that before creating an instance, all plotting should have taken place and the relevant artists should be saved\n",
        "#ArtistAnimation(fig, artists, *args, **kwargs)\n",
        "#interval: Delay between frames in milliseconds\n",
        "#blit : bool, optional. Controls whether blitting is used to optimize drawing. Defaults to False\n",
        "animated_results_2 = animation.ArtistAnimation(fig, frames, interval=70, repeat=False)\n"
